description:
FEAR ITSELF TIE-IN FOUR MARVEL HEROES SUCCUMB TO FEAR ITSELF! Do you fear... your protectors turning on you? Man-Thing has gone mad as fear consumes the world, and Manhattan will burn. The only heroes that seek to stop him have given into fear themselves, and no one is safe! Ryan Bodenheim illustrates the dark side of the Marvel universe as a team of monstrously talented artists spotlight Fear Itself, each through the eyes of a fallen hero. Eisner Hall of Famer Michael Kaluta leads the charge, transforming Nighthawk into the most frightening vigilante you’ve ever seen!

Collected in Fear Itself: Deadpool/Fearsome Four.

Translated into Spanish.
name: Fear Itself: Fearsome Four

deck: Started in 1975 by the same authors of Blueberry.
description:
Started in 1975 by the same authors of Blueberry, Charlier and Giraud (Moebius). After Charlier death it has become a volume for children.
 
The three first issues were originally part of the Blueberry volume. Since issue #4, Colin Wilson was the penciller, and since issue #10, it is Michel Blanc-Dumont. Jean-Michel Chariler kept writting the plots until his death, in 1989. Since issue #7, Corteggiani is the writter. 
 
Like the Blueberry volume, it spent a few years being published outside Dargaud (Novedi and Alpen).
name: La Jeunesse de Blueberry

deck: The Godfather meets There will be blood.
description: The fight of the Benson brothers to inherit their father's oil empire has already been a success despite having only three issues published so far. It might be too easy to call it "The Godfather meets There will be Blood". The story is well written by Fabien Nury but the drawings of Renaud Garreta are probably the main hook. It also revisits some historical events of the last century, like the mexican revolution and how did it affect the oil business.
name: Le Maître de Benson Gate

description: Fabien Nury gets inspiration from Lovecraft stories and the archives from the 1920's Dry Law in the US to write a two-issues volume (what french editors like to call diptych) where he mixes the economical and social atmosphere of that decade with the world of the dead and necromancy. Penciller Jack Manini emphasizes the esoteric feeling with a lot of mute frames and, what a better place for a story like this one than New Orleans?
name: Necromancy

description:
In Ancient Greece, the Gods act among the people. Tirésias, a dissolute warrior, suffers an unusual Gods' punishment. Serge Le Tendre recreates briliantly the life in Thebes and the relation with mithology. Christian Rossi's drawings and colours are gorgeous. It can be considered a feminist comic.
 
Dargaud published both issues in one, in 2011.
name: Tirésias
